				<strong class="title">General Comment</strong>To me, I always felt he was singing to his muse.  That may or may not be true, but that's what I like to think.  <br />
<br />
"Twas in another lifetime, one of toil and blood" - looking back on the early part of his career.<br />
"blackness was a virtue" - everyone was trying to immitate the blues artists.<br />
"the road was full of mud" - but a legitimate artist had to pay true dues to reach his destination.<br />
"I came in from the wilderness, a creature void of form" - he's just another folk artist without a voice.<br />
"come in she said I'll give you..." - I like to think he found SOMETHING that helped channel his emotions.  The lines proceeding this have nothing to do with women - it has to be taken in context.<br />
<br />
Again, this is just what I like to think and ALWAYS WILL because it speaks to me.  				
