			<div class="text" id="comment-73015974167">

				<strong class="title">General Comment</strong>Here's what happens in this story, in chronological order with verses referenced (as the song is definitely not in order)<br />
<br />
First thing's first. He "offered up his innocence, and got repaid with scorn." (while we're at it, does that sound like anyone else in history?) (verse 9)<br />
<br />
That scorn came in the form of a "lethal dose." ( verse 9)<br />
<br />
After that he "came in from the wilderness." (died?) and was a "creature devoid of form." (oh yeah, definitely died) (verse 1)<br />
<br />
The world he just "died in" had "roads full of mud" and "blackness was a virtue." Kinda sounds like a place where you could get lethally poisoned while people played dice for your pants. (verse 1)<br />
<br />
Ok, so he's standing there after having just died. And he hears a females voice say "come in, I'll give you shelter from the storm."  (verse 1)<br />
<br />
For a second, this guy and the voice just sit there. Nothing was said between them, and everything in this moment is "unresolved," If this guy had just died, he'd probably be wondering what's going to, you know, happen to him? But didn't he just say "there was little risk involved?" When the question of heaven/hell is before you, how could there not be any risk involved? Well, the guy says, "Try imagining a place that's always safe and warm." (verse 3)<br />
<br />
Queue angel (or whatever). The speaker of the voice emerges, the guy describes her as having silver bracelets, and flowers in her hair. She "gracefully" (full of GRACE, or quite literally, the love of god) walks up to him and removes his crown of thorns. Man that's some familiar symbolism. I mean, remember, when the guy TELLING this story had HIS innocence repaid with scorn? Just like, you know, JESUS. (I can't even type Jesus in capslock without hearing it in my head as a Southern Evangelist Preacher). (verse 5)<br />
<br />
Ok, so she takes his crown of thorns, and then SOMETHING happens. It's not really clear what. But That's pretty much the end of the "action." Wherever he was, with this angel, isn't described any further in the present tense. And then we can see that pretty much the other half of the verses are devoted to this guy's "thoughts" on his(possibly near-death) experience. <br />
<br />
I mean, he says "if I pass this way again, you can rest assured<br />
I'll always do my best for her, on that I give my word<br />
In a world of steel-eyed death, and men who are fighting to be warm.<br />
"Come in," she said, "I'll give you shelter from the storm." (verse 2)<br />
<br />
So at some point after his experience our(narrator/antagonist)guy is back in the crap world again (ours) promising someone that he will do his best to "live up" up to the beauty he experienced. Even in a world of ugliness, filled with men "fighting to be warm," and "steely-eyed death." He's changed by this experience, and strives for something greater. Maybe even godliness? Hey! Who else was godly while on Earth? Maaaybe the same guy that died sort of like our hero, and wore the same head-wear? Man Bob Dylan is obvious with his references....<br />
<br />
And the guy talks some more about the difficulties of living in our crap world after having experienced God or whatever it is he experienced. "There's a wall between us," he "got his signals crossed." It's been awhile since that "long-forgotten morn," and his connection with "her" (or god in some form) isn't quite as strong anymore. (verse 6)<br />
<br />
Oh, and in the verse missing from the above lyrics, he says "the bonds are broken, but can be retied." Is this sinking in? He visited god (bond) and is now back on earth (broken) and knows he will join god again (retied). But while he's here, he wants one more "journey through the woods," and THAT keeps his "spirit tied." Even though he knows that life on Earth is a "neverending battle." he isn't quite ready to leave. <br />
<br />
The only remaining verses in the song deal with this guy's changed perception of the world around him. <br />
<br />
The undertaker now "blows a futile horn." It's futile because our protagonist now knows what really awaits us after death. <br />
<br />
Someone comes up and talks to our guy about "babies wailin'" and "old men with broken teeth. Just like our guy used to be, this poor soul is lost and confused, and thinks it might be "hopeless and forlorn." Our guy knows that only life on Earth is hopeless and forlorn.<br />
<br />
Last paragraph ties it all in pretty straightforward. Yet again, he's talking about living in a "foreign country," although he's "bound to cross the line." (C'mon, is this not very obvious by this point?). "Beauty walks a razor's edge, someday I'll make it mine." Again, being godly while on Earth, returning back to the place where he experienced true beauty, etc. And finally, the last line is wishing he could go back to that wonderful place where he felt such warmth and love,"when GOD and HER were born." Notice the word "born." GOD and HER were sort of... born into his world, and his experience was kind of like giving birth, I guess, in that there's no "going back in." <br />
<br />
So yeah, Bob's a pretty cool dude, and I think he's capable of talking about way "more" than commentary on a war, or another love song. This song rocks.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
				
